# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: incident-management-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] The **Incident Command System** (**ICS**) is a standardized approach to the command, control, and coordination of emergency response providing a common hierarchy within which responders from multiple agencies can be effective.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] ICS was initially developed to address problems of inter-agency responses to wildfires in California but is now a component of the National Incident Management System (NIMS) in the US, where it has evolved into use in all-hazards situations, ranging from active shootings to hazmat scenes.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] In addition, ICS has acted as a pattern for similar approaches internationally.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] ICS consists of a standard management hierarchy and procedures for managing temporary incident(s) of any size.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] ICS procedures should be pre-established and sanctioned by participating authorities, and personnel should be well-trained before an incident.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] ICS includes procedures to select and form temporary management hierarchies to control funds, personnel, facilities, equipment, and communications.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] Personnel are assigned according to established standards and procedures previously sanctioned by participating authorities.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] ICS is a system designed to be used or applied from the time an incident occurs until the requirement for management and operations no longer exists.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] The ICS concept was formed in 1968 at a meeting of Fire Chiefs in Southern California.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] The program reflects the management hierarchy of the US Navy, and at first was used mainly to fight California wildfires.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] During the 1970s, ICS was fully developed during massive wildfire suppression efforts in California (FIRESCOPE) that followed a series of catastrophic wildfires, starting with the monumental Laguna fire in 1970.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] Property damage ran into the millions, and many people died or were injured.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] Studies determined that response problems are often related to communication and management deficiencies rather than a lack of resources or failure of tactics.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] Emergency managers determined that the existing management structures – frequently unique to each agency – did not scale to dealing with massive mutual aid responses involving dozens of distinct agencies and when these various agencies worked together their specific training and procedures clashed.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] As a result, a new command and control paradigm was collaboratively developed to create a consistent, integrated framework for the management of all incidents from small incidents to large, multi-agency emergencies.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] At the beginning of this work, despite the recognition that there were incident or field level shortfalls in organization and terminology, there was no mention of the need to develop an on the ground incident management system like ICS.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] Most of the efforts were focused on the multi-agency coordination challenges above the incident or field level.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] It was not until 1972 when Firefighting Resources of Southern California Organized for Potential Emergencies (FIRESCOPE) was formed that this need was recognized and the concept of ICS was first discussed.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] Also, ICS was originally called Field Command Operations System.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] ICS became a national model for command structures at a fire, crime scene, or major incident.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] ICS was used in New York City at the first attack on the World Trade Center in 1993.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] Additionally, it was mandated that NIMS (and thus ICS) must be used to manage emergencies to receive federal funding.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] The Superfund Amendment and Re-authorization Act title III mandated that all first responders to a hazardous materials emergency must be properly trained and equipped in accordance with 29 CFR 1910.120(q).
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] This standard represents OSHA's recognition of ICS.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] HSPD-5 and thus the National Incident Management System came about as a direct result of the terrorist attacks on 11 September 2001, which created numerous All-Hazard, Mass Casualty, multi-agency incidents.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] In the United States, ICS has been tested by more than 30 years of emergency and non-emergency applications.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] All levels of government are required to maintain differing levels of ICS training and private-sector organizations regularly use ICS for management of events.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] ICS is widespread in use from law enforcement to every-day business, as the basic goals of clear communication, accountability, and the efficient use of resources are common to incident and emergency management as well as daily operations.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] ICS is mandated by law for all Hazardous Materials responses nationally and for many other emergency operations in most states.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] In practice, virtually all emergency medical services and disaster response agencies use ICS, in part after the United States Department of Homeland Security mandated the use of ICS for emergency services throughout the United States as a condition for federal preparedness funding.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] As part of FEMA's National Response Plan (NRP), the system was expanded and integrated into the National Incident Management System (NIMS).
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] In Canada, the Incident Command System (ICS) has gained recognition and use within various governmental and emergency response agencies.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] Canadian authorities have embraced ICS principles as an effective framework for managing incidents and emergencies, ensuring a coordinated and efficient response.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] Federal, provincial, and territorial governments in Canada have adopted ICS as a key component of their emergency management strategies.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] This adoption is driven by the need to establish clear lines of communication, streamline resource allocation, and maintain accountability during critical incidents.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] Federal agencies such as Public Safety Canada promote the use of ICS to enhance the nation's emergency preparedness and response capabilities.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] Canada's proximity to the United States has facilitated the exchange of best practices in emergency management, including the adoption of ICS.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] Cross-border cooperation and training exercises have enabled Canadian agencies to align their incident management practices with those of their American counterparts.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] New Zealand has implemented a similar system, known as the Coordinated Incident Management System, Australia has the Australasian Inter-Service Incident Management System and British Columbia, Canada, has BCEMS developed by the Emergency Management and Climate Readiness.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] In a 2003 disaster reduction strategy report, a United Nations task force recommended the use of ICS as an international standard for wildfire incidents.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] In Brazil, ICS is also used by The Fire Department of the State of Rio de Janeiro (CBMERJ) and by the Civil Defense of the State of Rio de Janeiro in every emergency or large-scale event.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] As of 11 March 2024 in Mexico, the ICS is regulated by a federal norm: NOM-010-SSPC-2019.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] All municipal, state and federal agencies are obligated by this norm.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] Incidents are defined within ICS as *unplanned situations necessitating a response*.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] Events are defined within ICS as *planned situations*.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] Incident command is increasingly applied to events both in emergency management and non-emergency management settings.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] Each individual participating in the operation reports to only one supervisor.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] This eliminates the potential for individuals to receive conflicting orders from a variety of supervisors, thus increasing accountability, preventing freelancing, improving the flow of information, helping with the coordination of operational efforts, and enhancing operational safety.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] This concept is fundamental to the ICS chain of command structure.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] Individual response agencies previously developed their protocols separately, and subsequently developed their terminology separately.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] This can lead to confusion as a word may have a different meaning for each organization.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] When different organizations are required to work together, the use of common terminology is an essential element in team cohesion and communications, both internally and with other organizations responding to the incident.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] An incident command system promotes the use of a common terminology and has an associated glossary of terms that help bring consistency to position titles, the description of resources and how they can be organized, the type and names of incident facilities, and a host of other subjects.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] The use of common terminology is most evident in the titles of command roles, such as *Incident Commander*, *Safety Officer* or *Operations Section Chief*.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] Incidents are managed by aiming towards specific objectives.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] Objectives are ranked by priority; should be as specific as possible; must be attainable; and if possible given a working time-frame.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] Objectives are accomplished by first outlining strategies (general plans of action), then determining appropriate tactics (how the strategy will be executed) for the chosen strategy.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] Incident Command structure is organized in such a way as to expand and contract as needed by the incident scope, resources and hazards.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] Command is established in a top-down fashion, with the most important and authoritative positions established first.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] For example, Incident Command is established by the first arriving unit.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] Only positions that are required at the time should be established.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] In most cases, very few positions within the command structure will need to be activated.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] For example, a single fire truck at a dumpster fire will have the officer filling the role of IC, with no other roles required.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] As more trucks get added to a larger incident, more roles will be delegated to other officers and the Incident Commander (IC) role will probably be handed to a more-senior officer.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] Only in the largest and most complex operations would the full ICS organization be staffed.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] Conversely, as an incident scales down, roles will be merged back up the tree until there is just the IC role remaining.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] To limit the number of responsibilities and resources being managed by any individual, the ICS requires that any single person's span of control should be between three and seven individuals, with five being ideal.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] In other words, one manager should have no more than seven people working under them at any given time.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] If more than seven resources are being managed by an individual, then that individual is being overloaded and the command structure needs to be expanded by delegating responsibilities (e.g. by defining new sections, divisions, or task forces).
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] If fewer than three, then the position's authority can probably be absorbed by the next highest rung in the chain of command.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] One of the benefits of the ICS is that it allows a way to coordinate a set of organizations who may otherwise work together sporadically.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] While much training material emphasizes the hierarchical aspects of the ICS, it can also be seen as an inter-organizational network of responders.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] These network qualities allow the ICS flexibility and expertise of a range of organizations.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] But the network aspects of the ICS also create management challenges.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] One study of ICS after-action reports found that ICS tended to enjoy higher coordination when there was strong pre-existing trust and working relationships between members, but struggled when authority of the ICS was contested and when the networks of responders was highly diverse.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] The consolidated IAP is a very important component of the ICS that reduces freelancing and ensures a coordinated response.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] The content of the IAP is organized by a number of standardized ICS forms that allow for accurate and precise documentation of an incident.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] Each form serves a specific documentation role during incident operations; for example, the ICS 201 captures the initial situation and resources, while the ICS 204 serves as the primary accountability document for each Division or Group.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] Comprehensive resource management ensures that visibility is maintained over all resources so they can be moved quickly to support the preparation and response to an incident, and ensuring a graceful demobilization.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] It also applies to the classification of resources by type and kind, and the categorization of resources by their status.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] T-Cards (ICS 219, Resource Status Card) are most commonly used to track these resources.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] The cards are placed in T-Card racks located at an Incident Command Post for easy updating and visual tracking of resource status.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] Developing an integrated voice and data communications system, including equipment, systems, and protocols, must occur prior to an incident.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] At the ICS 200 level, the function of Information and Intelligence is added to the standard ICS staff as an option.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] This role is unique in ICS as it can be arranged in multiple ways based on the judgement of the Incident Commander and needs of the incident.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] At the ICS 300 level, the focus is on entry-level management of small-scale, all-hazards incidents with emphasis on the scalability of ICS.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] It acts as an introduction to the utilization of more than one agency and the possibility of numerous operational periods.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] It also involves an introduction to the emergency operations center.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] At the ICS 400 level, the focus is on large, complex incidents.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] Topics covered include the characteristics of incident complexity, the approaches to dividing an incident into manageable components, the establishment of an "area command", and the multi-agency coordination system (MACS).
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] ICS is organized by levels, with the supervisor of each level holding a unique title (e.g. only a person in charge of a section is labeled "chief"; a "director" is exclusively the person in charge of a branch).
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] ICS uses a standard set of facility nomenclature.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] ICS facilities include: **pre-designated incident facilities:** Response operations can form a complex structure that must be held together by response personnel working at different and often widely separate incident facilities.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] Each facility has unique location, space, equipment, materials, and supplies requirements that are often difficult to address, particularly at the outset of response operations.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] For this reason, responders should identify, pre-designate and pre-plan the layout of these facilities, whenever possible.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] On large or multi-level incidents, higher-level support facilities may be activated.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] ICS uses a standard set of equipment nomenclature.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] The importance of access to computer systems is becoming more common within the advancements to technology and to support the standardised approach to incident and emergency response.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] Commonly referred to within the Command and control structure within United States Army, computers and computer-based systems allow responders to interface with each other to have access to the latest information for decision making.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] See Incident Command Post (ICP) for more information.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] The "type" of resource describes the size or capability of a resource.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] For instance, a 50 kW (for a generator) or a 3-ton (for a truck).
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] Types are designed to be categorized as "Type 1" through "Type 5" formally, but in live incidents more specific information may be used.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] The "kind" of resource describes what the resource is.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] In both type and kind, the objective must be included in the resource request.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] This is done to widen the potential resource response.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] As an example, a resource request for a *small aircraft for aerial reconnaissance of a search and rescue scene* may be satisfied by a National Guard OH-58 Kiowa helicopter (type & kind: rotary-wing aircraft, Type II/III) or by a Civil Air Patrol Cessna 182 (type & kind: fixed-wing aircraft, Type I).
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] In this example, requesting only a fixed-wing or a rotary-wing, or requesting by type may prevent the other resource's availability from being known.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] Other reasons to transfer command include jurisdictional change if the incident moves locations or area of responsibility, or normal turnover of personnel due to extended incidents.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-command-system] The transfer of command process always includes a transfer of command briefing, which may be oral, written, or a combination of both.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] An incident is an event that could lead to loss of, or disruption to, an organization's operations, services, or functions.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] **Incident management** (**IcM**) refers to the activities an organization undertakes to identify, analyze, and correct hazards to prevent future recurrence.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] These incidents within a structured organization are normally dealt with by either an incident response team (IRT), an incident management team (IMT), or Incident Command System (ICS).
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] Without effective incident management, an incident can disrupt business operations, information security, IT systems, employees, customers, or other vital business functions.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] An incident is an event that may lead to the loss of, or disruption to, an organization's operations, services or functions.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] Incident management (IcM) is a term describing the activities of an organization to identify, analyze, and correct hazards to prevent a future re-occurrence.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] If not managed, an incident can escalate into an emergency, crisis or disaster.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] Incident management is therefore the process of limiting the potential disruption caused by such an event, followed by a return to business as usual.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] Physical incident management is the real-time response that may last for hours, days, or longer.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] The United Kingdom Cabinet Office has produced the National Recovery Guidance (NRG), which is aimed at local responders as part of the implementation of the Civil Contingencies Act 2004 (CCA).
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] It describes the response as the following: "Response encompasses the actions taken to deal with the immediate effects of an emergency.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] In many scenarios, it is likely to be relatively short and to last for a matter of hours or days – rapid implementation of arrangements for collaboration, coordination and communication is, therefore, vital.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] Response encompasses the effort to deal not only with the direct effects of the emergency itself (eg fighting fires, rescuing individuals) but also the indirect effects (eg disruption, media interest)".
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] This again shows the importance of not just good planning but the effective allocation of resources to treat the risk.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] Incident management in critical infrastructure environments involves coordinated response activities designed to protect essential services whose disruption may impact public safety, economic stability, or national security.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] Unlike incident management in purely informational or corporate IT contexts, critical infrastructure incidents often involve operational technology, physical processes, safety systems, and regulatory obligations.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] Critical infrastructure incident management typically emphasizes early detection, structured escalation, cross-functional coordination, and continuity of operations.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] Incidents may originate from cyber events, physical failures, human error, natural hazards, or combined (hybrid) causes, requiring integrated response across engineering, operations, security, executive leadership, and external authorities.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] Because infrastructure sectors are highly interdependent, incident management approaches in these environments often account for cascading effects across energy, communications, transportation, healthcare, and other essential services.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] As a result, planning and response activities commonly incorporate predefined roles, decision authorities, communication protocols, and recovery objectives aligned with safety and resilience requirements.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] Today, an important role is played by a Computer Security Incident Response Team (CSIRT), due to the rise of internet crime, and is a common example of an incident faced by companies in developed nations all across the world.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] For example, if an organization discovers that an intruder has gained unauthorized access to a computer system, the CSIRT would analyze the situation, determine the breadth of the compromise, and take corrective action.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] Currently, over half of the world's hacking attempts on Trans National Corporations (TNCs) have taken place in North America (57%).
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] A Computer Security Incident Response team can provide a secure environment for an organization, and has become a large part of the design of many modern networking teams.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] Incidents within a structured organization are normally dealt with by either an incident response team (IRT), or an incident management team (IMT).
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] These are often designated beforehand or during the event and are placed in control of the organization while the incident is being addressed, to restore normal functions.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] The incident commander manages the response to a security incident and leads the members of the incident response team(s) through the process, as defined by the Incident Command System (ICS).
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] Usually, as part of the wider management process in private organizations, incident management is followed by post-incident analysis where it is determined why the incident happened despite precautions and controls.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] This analysis is normally overseen by the leaders of the organization, with the view of preventing a repetition of the incident through precautionary measures and often changes in policy.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] This information is then used as feedback to further develop the security policy and/or its practical implementation.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] In the United States, the National Incident Management System, developed by the Department of Homeland Security, integrates effective practices in emergency management into a comprehensive national framework.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] This often results in a higher level of contingency planning, exercise and training, as well as an evaluation of the management of the incident.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] Incident management frameworks for critical infrastructure commonly follow a lifecycle-based approach that includes incident detection, classification, response coordination, containment, recovery, and post-incident review.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] These frameworks are designed to support timely decision-making while balancing safety, operational continuity, and regulatory compliance.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] In critical infrastructure contexts, such frameworks often integrate elements from emergency management systems, cybersecurity incident response practices, and operational risk management models.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] The goal is to enable organizations to respond effectively under high-consequence conditions while maintaining control over complex technical and organizational dependencies.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] Practitioner-oriented literature provides detailed guidance on applying lifecycle-based incident management frameworks within industrial and critical infrastructure environments, including considerations for operational technology, safety, and cross-sector coordination.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] During the root cause analysis, human factors should be assessed.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] James Reason conducted a study into the understanding of adverse effects of human factors.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] The study found that major incident investigations, such as Piper Alpha and Kings Cross Underground Fire, made it clear that the causes of the accidents were distributed widely within and outside the organization.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] There are two types of events: active failure—an action that has immediate effects and has the likelihood to cause an accident—and latent or delayed action—events can take years to have an effect and are usually combined with triggering events that then cause the accident.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] Latent failures are created as the result of decisions taken at the higher echelons of an organisation.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] Their damaging consequences may lie dormant for a long time, only becoming evident when they combine with local triggering factors (e.g., the spring tide, the loading difficulties at Zeebrugge harbour, etc.) to breach the system's defences.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] Decisions taken in the higher echelons of an organization can trigger the events towards an accident becoming more likely, the planning, scheduling, forecasting, designing, policymaking, etc., can have a slow burning effect.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] The actual unsafe act that triggers an accident can be traced back through the organization and the subsequent failures can be exposed, showing the accumulation of latent failures within the system as a whole that led to the accident becoming more likely and ultimately happening.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] Better improvement action can be applied, and reduce the likelihood of the event happening again.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] Incident management is an important part of IT service management (ITSM) process area.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] The first goal of the incident management process is to restore a normal service operation as quickly as possible and to minimize the impact on business operations, thus ensuring that the best possible levels of service quality and availability are maintained.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] 'Normal service operation' is defined here as service operation within service-level agreement (SLA).
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] It is one process area within the broader ITIL and ISO 20000 environment.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] an unplanned interruption to an IT service or reduction in the quality of an IT service or a failure of a Configuration Item that has not yet impacted an IT service (for example failure of one disk from a mirror set).
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] The ITIL incident management process *ensures that normal service operation is restored as quickly as possible and the business impact is minimized.* **ITIL Service Operation*.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] The HIPAA Breach Notification Rule further requires notification to affected individuals within 60 days when unsecured protected health information is compromised, with breaches affecting 500 or more individuals reported to HHS and the media.
[src:incident-management-deep/incident-management] The proposed rule also mandates annual testing and revision of incident response and contingency plans.
[src:incident-management-deep/it-service-management] Organizational ITSM process execution, especially for workflows, can benefit significantly from being supported with specialized software tools.
[src:incident-management-deep/it-service-management] A service desk is a primary IT function within the discipline of IT service management (ITSM) as defined by ITIL.
[src:incident-management-deep/it-service-management] It is intended to provide a *Single Point of Contact* (SPOC) to meet the communication needs of both users and IT staff, and to satisfy both customer and IT provider objectives.
[src:incident-management-deep/it-service-management] *User* refers to the actual user of the service, while *customer* refers to the entity that is paying for the service.
[src:incident-management-deep/it-service-management] ITSM tools are frequently applied to other aspects of business; this practice is often called enterprise service management (ESM).
[src:incident-management-deep/it-service-management] A key initiative in ITSM is the automation of routine tasks, enabling personnel to focus on higher-priority responsibilities; this is known as IT process automation.
[src:incident-management-deep/it-service-management] The ITIL approach considers the service desk to be the central point of contact between service providers and users/customers on a day-to-day basis.
[src:incident-management-deep/it-service-management] It is also a focal point for reporting *incidents* (disruptions or potential disruptions in service availability or quality) and for submitting *service requests* (routine requests for services).
[src:incident-management-deep/it-service-management] ITIL regards a call center or help desk as similar kinds of tech support which provide only a portion of what a service desk can offer.
[src:incident-management-deep/it-service-management] A service desk has a broader and user-centered approach which is designed to provide the user with an informed single point of contact for all IT activities.
[src:incident-management-deep/it-service-management] A service desk facilitates the integration of business processes into the service management infrastructure.
[src:incident-management-deep/it-service-management] Computer emergency response teams (CERT) are specifically dedicated to computer security incidents.
[src:incident-management-deep/it-service-management] ITSM is similar to other IT and general management approaches, especially information security management and software engineering.
[src:incident-management-deep/it-service-management] Consequently, IT service management frameworks have been influenced by other standards and adopted concepts from them, e.g.
[src:incident-management-deep/it-service-management] There are international, chapter-based professional associations, such as the IT Service Management Forum (itSMF), and HDI.
[src:incident-management-deep/it-service-management] These organizations' main goal is to foster the exchange of experiences and ideas between ITSM users.
[src:incident-management-deep/it-service-management] To this end, national and local itSMF and HDI chapters (LIGs or local interest groups for itSMF) organize conferences and workshops.
[src:incident-management-deep/it-service-management] Some of them also contribute to the translation of ITSM framework documents into their respective languages or publish their own ITSM guides.
[src:incident-management-deep/it-service-management] There are several service management certifications that include, but are not limited to, ITILv4, TOGAF or COBIT.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Effective incident management is key to limiting the disruption caused by an incident and restoring normal business operations as quickly as possible.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] If you haven’t gamed out your response to potential incidents in advance, principled incident management can go out the window in real-life situations.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] This chapter walks through a portrait of an incident that spirals out of control due to ad hoc incident management practices, outlines a well-managed approach to the incident, and reviews how the same incident might have played out if handled with well-functioning incident management.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Put yourself in the shoes of Mary, the on-call engineer for The Firm.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] It’s 2 p.m. on a Thursday afternoon and your pager has just exploded.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Black-box monitoring tells you that your service has stopped serving *any* traffic in an entire datacenter.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] With a sigh, you put down your coffee and set about the job of fixing it.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] A few minutes into the task, another alert tells you that a second datacenter has stopped serving.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Then the third out of your five datacenters fails.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] To exacerbate the situation, there is more traffic than the remaining datacenters can handle, so they start to overload.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Before you know it, the service is overloaded and unable to serve any requests.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] You stare at the logs for what seems like an eternity.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Thousands of lines of logging suggest there’s an error in one of the recently updated modules, so you decide to revert the servers to the previous release.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] When you see that the rollback hasn’t helped, you call Josephine, who wrote most of the code for the now-hemorrhaging service.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Reminding you that it’s 3:30 a.m. in her time zone, she blearily agrees to log in and take a look.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Your colleagues Sabrina and Robin start poking around from their own terminals.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Time passes; the two remaining datacenters fail completely.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Unbeknown to you, sleep-addled Josephine called Malcolm.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] He had a brainwave: something about CPU affinity.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] He felt certain that he could optimize the remaining server processes if he could just deploy this one simple change to the production environment, so he did so.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Within seconds, the servers restarted, picking up the change.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Note that everybody in the preceding scenario was doing their job, as they saw it.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] A few common hazards caused this incident to spiral out of control.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] We tend to hire people like Mary for their technical prowess.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] So it’s not surprising that she was busy making operational changes to the system, trying valiantly to solve the problem.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] She wasn’t in a position to think about the bigger picture of how to mitigate the problem because the technical task at hand was overwhelming.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] For the same reason, Mary was far too busy to communicate clearly.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Nobody knew what actions their coworkers were taking.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Business leaders were angry, customers were frustrated, and other engineers who could have lent a hand in debugging or fixing the issue weren’t used effectively.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Malcolm was making changes to the system with the best of intentions.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] However, he didn’t coordinate with his coworkers—not even Mary, who was technically in charge of troubleshooting.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] His changes made a bad situation far worse.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Incident management skills and practices exist to channel the energies of enthusiastic individuals.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Google’s incident management system is based on the Incident Command System,79 which is known for its clarity and scalability.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] A well-designed incident management process has the following features.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] It’s important to make sure that everybody involved in the incident knows their role and doesn’t stray onto someone else’s turf.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Somewhat counterintuitively, a clear separation of responsibilities allows individuals more autonomy than they might otherwise have, since they need not second-guess their colleagues.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] If the load on a given member becomes excessive, that person needs to ask the planning lead for more staff.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] They should then delegate work to others, a task that might entail creating subincidents.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Alternatively, a role leader might delegate system components to colleagues, who report high-level information back up to the leaders.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] The incident commander holds the high-level state about the incident.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] They structure the incident response task force, assigning responsibilities according to need and priority.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] , the commander holds all positions that they have not delegated.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] If appropriate, they can remove roadblocks that prevent Ops from working most effectively.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] The Ops lead works with the incident commander to respond to the incident by applying operational tools to the task at hand.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] The operations team should be the only group modifying the system during an incident.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] This person is the public face of the incident response task force.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Their duties most definitely include issuing periodic updates to the incident response team and stakeholders (usually via email), and may extend to tasks such as keeping the incident document accurate and up to date.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] The planning role supports Ops by dealing with longer-term issues, such as filing bugs, ordering dinner, arranging handoffs, and tracking how the system has diverged from the norm so it can be reverted once the incident is resolved.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Interested parties need to understand where they can interact with the incident commander.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] In many situations, locating the incident task force members into a central designated "War Room" is appropriate.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Others teams may prefer to work at their desks, keeping alert to incident updates via email and IRC.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Google has found IRC to be a huge boon in incident response.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] IRC is very reliable and can be used as a log of communications about this event, and such a record is invaluable in keeping detailed state changes in mind.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] We’ve also written bots that log incident-related traffic (which is helpful for postmortem analysis), and other bots that log events such as alerts to the channel.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] IRC is also a convenient medium over which geographically distributed teams can coordinate.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] The incident commander’s most important responsibility is to keep a living incident document.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] This can live in a wiki, but should ideally be editable by several people concurrently.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Most of our teams use Google Docs, though Google Docs SRE use Google Sites: after all, depending on the software you are trying to fix as part of your incident management system is unlikely to end well.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] See Example Incident State Document for a sample incident document.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] This living doc can be messy, but must be functional.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Using a template makes generating this documentation easier, and keeping the most important information at the top makes it more usable.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Retain this documentation for postmortem analysis and, if necessary, meta analysis.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] It’s essential that the post of incident commander be clearly handed off at the end of the working day.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] If you’re handing off command to someone at another location, you can simply and safely update the new incident commander over the phone or a video call.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Once the new incident commander is fully apprised, the outgoing commander should be explicit in their handoff, specifically stating, "You’re now the incident commander, okay?", and should not leave the call until receiving firm acknowledgment of handoff.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] The handoff should be communicated to others working on the incident so that it’s clear who is leading the incident management efforts at all times.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Now let’s examine how this incident might have played out if it were handled using principles of incident management.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] It’s 2 p.m., and Mary is into her third coffee of the day.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] The pager’s harsh tone surprises her, and she gulps the drink down.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Problem: a datacenter has stopped serving traffic.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Shortly another alert fires, and the second datacenter out of five is out of order.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Because this is a rapidly growing issue, she knows that she’ll benefit from the structure of her incident management framework.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] "Can you take command?" Nodding her agreement, Sabrina quickly gets a rundown of what’s occurred thus far from Mary.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] She captures these details in an email that she sends to a prearranged mailing list.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Sabrina recognizes that she can’t yet scope the impact of the incident, so she asks for Mary’s assessment.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Mary responds, "Users have yet to be impacted; let’s just hope we don’t lose a third datacenter." Sabrina records Mary’s response in a live incident document.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] When the third alert fires, Sabrina sees the alert among the debugging chatter on IRC and quickly follows up to the email thread with an update.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] The thread keeps VPs abreast of the high-level status without bogging them down in minutiae.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Sabrina asks an external communications representative to start drafting user messaging.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] She then follows up with Mary to see if they should contact the developer on-call (currently Josephine).
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Receiving Mary’s approval, Sabrina loops in Josephine.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] By the time Josephine logs in, Robin has already volunteered to help out.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Sabrina reminds both Robin and Josephine that they are to prioritize any tasks delegated to them by Mary, and that they must keep Mary informed of any additional actions they take.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Robin and Josephine quickly familiarize themselves with the current situation by reading the incident document.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] By now, Mary has tried the old binary release and found it wanting: she mutters this to Robin, who updates IRC to say that this attempted fix didn’t work.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Sabrina pastes this update into the live incident management document.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] At 5 p.m., Sabrina starts finding replacement staff to take on the incident, as she and her colleagues are about to go home.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] A brief phone conference takes place at 5:45 so everyone is aware of the current situation.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] At 6 p.m., they hand off their responsibilities to their colleagues in the sister office.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Mary returns to work the following morning to find that her transatlantic colleagues have assumed responsibility for the bug, mitigated the problem, closed the incident, and started work on the postmortem.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Problem solved, she brews some fresh coffee and settles down to plan structural improvements so problems of this category don’t afflict the team again.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] It is better to declare an incident early and then find a simple fix and close out the incident than to have to spin up the incident management framework hours into a burgeoning problem.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Set clear conditions for declaring an incident.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Incident management proficiency atrophies quickly when it’s not in constant use.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] So how can engineers keep their incident management skills up to date—handle more incidents?
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Fortunately, the incident management framework can apply to other operational changes that need to span time zones and/or teams.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] If you use the framework frequently as a regular part of your change management procedures, you can easily follow this framework when an actual incident occurs.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] If your organization performs disaster-recovery testing (you should, it’s *fun*: see [Kri12]), incident management should be part of that testing process.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] We often role-play the response to an on-call issue that has already been solved, perhaps by colleagues in another location, to further familiarize ourselves with incident management.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] We’ve found that by formulating an incident management strategy in advance, structuring this plan to scale smoothly, and regularly putting the plan to use, we were able to reduce our mean time to recovery and provide staff a less stressful way to work on emergent problems.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] Any organization concerned with reliability would benefit from pursuing a similar strategy.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] 78An earlier version of this chapter appeared as an article in *;login:* (April 2015, vol.
[src:incident-management-deep/managing-incidents] 79See *https://www.fema.gov/national-incident-management-system* for further details.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] In science and reliability engineering, **root-cause analysis** (**RCA**) is a method of problem solving used for identifying the root causes of faults or problems.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] It is widely used in IT operations, manufacturing, telecommunications, industrial process control, accident analysis (e.g., in aviation, rail transport, or nuclear plants), medical diagnosis, the healthcare industry (e.g., for epidemiology).
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Root-cause analysis is a form of inductive inference (first create a theory, or *root*, based on empirical evidence, or *causes*) and deductive inference (test the theory, i.e., the underlying causal mechanisms, with empirical data).
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Establish a causal graph between the root-cause and the problem.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] RCA generally serves as input to a remediation process whereby corrective actions are taken to prevent the problem from recurring.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] The name of this process varies between application domains.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] According to ISO/IEC 31010, RCA may include these techniques: five whys, failure mode and effects analysis (FMEA), fault tree analysis, Ishikawa diagrams, and Pareto analysis.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] There are essentially two ways of repairing faults and solving problems in science and engineering.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Reactive management consists of reacting quickly after the problem occurs, by treating the symptoms.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] This type of management is implemented by reactive systems, self-adaptive systems, self-organized systems, and complex adaptive systems.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] The goal here is to react quickly and alleviate the effects of the problem as soon as possible.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Proactive management, conversely, consists of preventing problems from occurring.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Many techniques can be used for this purpose, ranging from good practices in design to analyzing in detail problems that have already occurred and taking actions to make sure they never recur.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Speed is not as important here as the accuracy and precision of the diagnosis.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] The focus is on addressing the real cause of the problem rather than its effects.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Root-cause analysis is often used in proactive management to identify the root cause of a problem, that is, the factor that was the leading cause.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] It is customary to refer to the "root cause" in singular form, but one or several factors may constitute the *root cause(s)* of the problem under study.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] A factor is considered the "root cause" of a problem if removing it prevents the problem from recurring.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Conversely, a "causal factor" is a contributing action that affects an incident/event's outcome but is not the root cause.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Although removing a causal factor can benefit an outcome, it does not prevent its recurrence with certainty.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] A great way to look at the proactive/reactive picture is to consider the Bowtie Risk Assessment model.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] In the center of the model is the event or accident.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] To the left, are the anticipated hazards and the line of defenses put in place to prevent those hazards from causing events.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] The line of defense is the regulatory requirements, applicable procedures, physical barriers, and cyber barriers that are in place to manage operations and prevent events.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] A great way to use root-cause analysis is to proactively evaluate the effectiveness of those defenses by comparing actual performance against applicable requirements, identifying performance gaps, and then closing the gaps to strengthen those defenses.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] If an event occurs, then we are on the right side of the model, the reactive side where the emphasis is on identifying the root causes and mitigating the damage.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Imagine an investigation into a machine that stopped because it was overloaded and the fuse blew.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Investigation shows that the machine was overloaded because it had a bearing that was not being sufficiently lubricated.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] The investigation proceeds further and finds that the automatic lubrication mechanism had a pump that was not pumping sufficiently, hence the lack of lubrication.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Investigation of the pump shows that it has a worn shaft.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Investigation of why the shaft was worn discovers that there is not an adequate mechanism to prevent metal scrap getting into the pump; this enabled scrap to get into the pump and damage it.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] The apparent root cause of the problem is that metal scrap can contaminate the lubrication system.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Fixing this problem ought to prevent the whole sequence of events from recurring.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] The *real* root cause could be a design issue if there is no filter to prevent the metal scrap getting into the system.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Or if it has a filter that was blocked due to a lack of routine inspection, then the *real* root cause is a maintenance issue.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Compare this with an investigation that does not find the root cause: replacing the fuse, the bearing, or the lubrication pump will probably allow the machine to go back into operation for a while.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] However, there is a risk that the problem will simply recur until the root cause is dealt with.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] In general terms, for the investigating team, such as quality and engineering personnel, vernacularly speaking, it commonly takes around 5 times asking "why".
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] The above example does not include cost/benefit analysis: does the cost of replacing one or more machines exceed the cost of downtime until the fuse is replaced?
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] This situation is sometimes referred to as *the cure being worse than the disease*.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] This can help explain the problem of the cure being worse than the disease.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Costs to consider go beyond finances when considering the personnel who operate the machinery.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Ultimately, the goal is to prevent downtime; but more so prevent catastrophic injuries.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Despite the different approaches among the various schools of root-cause analysis and the specifics of each application domain, RCA generally follows the same steps.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Effective problem statements and event descriptions (as failures, for example) are helpful and usually required to ensure the execution of appropriate root-cause analyses.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Problem statements are the North Star of the RCA as it keeps the team focused on what they are investigating and prevents them from going astray.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Most RCAs begin with a fact finding session to gather available information such as witness statements, the chronology of events and applicable requirements for the evolutions that were taking place at the time of the event.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] The information can be used to establish a sequence of events or timeline for the event, and to identify the line of the defenses that should have prevented the event (i.e. the administrative requirements, and physical and cyber barriers).
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Available databases should also be queried and analyzed (such as corrective action program and safety program databases), and data analysis tools such as Pareto charts, process maps, fault trees, and other tools that provide insights into performance gaps.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Any number of data analysis tools can be brought to bear, including data analysis tools from Lean Six Sigma, statistical analysis tools, and others such as hierarchical clustering and data-mining solutions (such as graph-theory-based data mining).
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Another consists in comparing the situation under investigation with past situations stored in case libraries, using case-based reasoning tools and can include change analysis, comparative timeline analysis and task analysis.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] After identifying the defenses in place that should have prevented the event or accident, an analysis of defenses (traditionally called Barrier Analysis) can be conducted in every case, including non-RCA investigations.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] These initial gaps in performance are merely symptoms of deeper-seated causes.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] These symptomatic performance gaps are used to develop lines of inquiry questions as outlined below, to pursue the symptoms back to their points of origin (i.e. the root causes) using cause-and-effect analysis.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] After gathering available information, organizing it into charts with timelines and other data, after analyzing available data, and after conducting an analysis of defenses, those insights are used to generate questions.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] These questions become lines of inquiry for cause-and-effect analysis.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] There should not be any curiosity questions, questions that reflect "confirmation bias" (i.e. asking a leading question so they answer what the RCA team thinks are the causes), or questions that are accusatory in nature that will cause those helping the investigation to close down and withdraw.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Once a robust set of lines of inquiry questions has been developed from the factual evidence collected, the applicable requirements, and an analysis of the available data, those questions can be taken to the organization's subject matter experts.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] This begins the process of cause-and-effect analysis.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Once a question is posed to the affected organization, their answer is used to pose a follow-up Socratic questions.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Socratic questions keep the investigation flowing down to the next deeper causal factors until the organization runs out of answers, or the last causal factor is beyond the organization's control.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] There are many skills involved in conducting an effective cause-and-effect analysis, including facilitation skills, communication skills, and Socratic questioning.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] When conducted properly, this will take the RCA down to the deepest-seated root causes.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] A word of caution: Ishikawa or the Fishbone Diagram, and the 5-Whys methods, are not rigorous enough for conducting a root-cause analysis.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] The Fishbone is from the 1940s and the 5-Whys is from the 1930, and there are much more advanced methods available.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Look for methods that were developed in this century (the year 2000 and later), as they are more likely to account for the new dynamics of the modern sociotechnical work environments.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] The best way to chart the results of an RCA investigation is to start populating the final chart from the start.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] This process has become much easier with the advent of virtual whiteboards.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] In a single virtual whiteboard, the timelines, lines of defenses, data analysis, lines of inquiry questions, cause-and-effect analysis, root causes, and corrective action plan can be displayed.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] The Extent of Cause reviews are conducted to determine the extent of the damage or impact that the root causes and contributing factors had on humans, equipment, or facilities.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Extent of Cause reviews are an Achilles heel in the vast majority of organizations and a primary reason why RCAs and corrective action plans fail to prevent recurrence.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Also, care must be taken to avoid corrective action plans that simply add more administrative requirements and more training to the organization.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] To avoid this, use the Hierarchy of Hazard Controls and Lean Mistake Proofing as guidelines for developing effective corrective actions that have a much higher likelihood of preventing recurrence.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] After a pre-determined period after the implementation of the corrective action plan, an effectiveness review is scheduled to evaluate the effectiveness of those corrective actions.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] This requires specifying a set of metrics or indicators that will be monitored prior to and after the corrective actions are implemented, so their impact can be measured.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] If the desired results are not achieved, which in most cases is a significant reduction in the magnitude or frequency of the event or problem, then the RCA must be reopened as it was not effective.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] To be effective, root-cause analysis must be performed systematically.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] The process enables the chance to not miss any other important details.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] A team effort is typically required, and ideally all persons involved should arrive at the same conclusion.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] In aircraft accident analyses, for example, the conclusions of the investigation and the root causes that are identified must be backed up by documented evidence.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] The goal of RCA is to identify the root cause of the problem with the intent to stop the problem from recurring or worsening.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] The next step is to trigger long-term corrective actions to address the root cause identified during RCA, and make sure that the problem does not resurface.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Correcting a problem is not formally part of RCA, however; these are different steps in a problem-solving process known as fault management in IT and telecommunications, repair in engineering, remediation in aviation, environmental remediation in ecology, therapy in medicine, etc.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Root-cause analysis is used in many application domains.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] RCA is specifically called out in the United States Code of Federal Regulations in many of the Titles.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] TITLE 14 - AERONAUTICS AND SPACE >>> 14 CFR Chapter III, Subchapter C, Part 437, Subpart C, §437.73 Anomaly recording, reporting and implementation of corrective actions.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] A permittee must identify all root causes of each anomaly and implement all corrective actions for each anomaly.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] TITLE 21 - FOOD AND DRUG >>> 21 CFR Subpart J: 21CFR820.100(a) – Corr./Preventive Action: (A) Each manufacturer shall establish and maintain procedures for implementing corrective and preventive action.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] The example above illustrates how RCA can be used in manufacturing.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] RCA is also routinely used in industrial process control, e.g. to control the production of chemicals (quality control).
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] RCA is also used for failure analysis in engineering and maintenance.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Root-cause analysis is frequently used in IT and telecommunications to detect the root causes of serious problems.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] For example, in the ITIL service management framework, the goal of incident management is to resume a faulty IT service as soon as possible (reactive management), whereas problem management deals with solving recurring problems for good by addressing their root causes (proactive management).
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Another example is the computer security incident management process, where root-cause analysis is often used to investigate security breaches.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] RCA is also used in conjunction with business activity monitoring and complex event processing to analyze faults in business processes.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Its use in the IT industry cannot always be compared to its use in safety critical industries, since in normality the use of RCA in IT industry is *not* supported by pre-existing fault trees or other design specs.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Instead a mixture of debugging, event based detection and monitoring systems (where the services are individually modelled) is normally supporting the analysis.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Training and supporting tools like simulation or different in-depth runbooks for all expected scenarios do not exist, instead they are created after the fact based on issues seen as 'worthy'.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] As a result the analysis is often limited to those things that have monitoring/observation interfaces and not the actual planned/seen function with focus on verification of inputs and outputs.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Hence, the saying "there is no root cause" has become common in the IT industry.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] In the domains of health and safety, RCA is routinely used in medicine (diagnosis) and epidemiology (e.g., to identify the source of an infectious disease), where causal inference methods often require both clinical and statistical expertise to make sense of the complexities of the processes.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] RCA is used in environmental science (e.g., to analyze environmental disasters), accident analysis (aviation and rail industry), and occupational safety and health.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] In the manufacture of medical devices, pharmaceuticals, food, and dietary supplements, root-cause analysis is a regulatory requirement.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] RCA is also used in change management, risk management, and systems analysis.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Without delving in the idiosyncrasies of specific problems, several general conditions can make RCA more difficult than it may appear at first sight.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] First, important information is often missing because it is generally not possible, in practice, to monitor everything and store all monitoring data for a long time.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Second, gathering data and evidence, and classifying them along a timeline of events to the final problem, can be nontrivial.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] In telecommunications, for instance, distributed monitoring systems typically manage between a million and a billion events per day.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Finding a few relevant events in such a mass of irrelevant events is asking to find the proverbial needle in a haystack.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Third, there may be more than one root cause for a given problem, and this multiplicity can make the causal graph very difficult to establish.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Fourth, causal graphs often have many levels, and root-cause analysis terminates at a level that is "root" to the eyes of the investigator.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Switching vendors may have been due to management's desire to save money, and a failure to consult with engineering staff on the implication of the change on maintenance procedures.
[src:incident-management-deep/root-cause-analysis] Thus, while the "root cause" shown above may have prevented the quoted recurrence, it would not have prevented other – perhaps more severe – failures affecting other machines.
[src:incident-management-deep/site-reliability-engineering] Site Reliability Engineering originated at Google with Benjamin Treynor Sloss, who founded SRE team in 2003.
[src:incident-management-deep/site-reliability-engineering] The concept expanded within the software development industry, leading various companies to employ site reliability engineers.
[src:incident-management-deep/site-reliability-engineering] By March 2016, Google had more than 1,000 site reliability engineers on staff.
[src:incident-management-deep/site-reliability-engineering] Dedicated SRE teams are common at larger web development companies.
[src:incident-management-deep/site-reliability-engineering] In middle-sized and smaller companies, DevOps teams sometimes perform SRE, as well.
[src:incident-management-deep/site-reliability-engineering] Organizations that have adopted the concept include Airbnb, Dropbox, IBM, LinkedIn, Netflix, and Wikimedia.
[src:incident-management-deep/site-reliability-engineering] Site reliability engineers (SREs) are responsible for a combination of system availability, latency, performance, efficiency, change management, monitoring, emergency response, and capacity planning.
[src:incident-management-deep/site-reliability-engineering] SREs often have backgrounds in software engineering, systems engineering, and/or system administration.
[src:incident-management-deep/site-reliability-engineering] The focuses of SRE include automation, system design, and improvements to system resilience.
[src:incident-management-deep/site-reliability-engineering] SRE is considered a specific implementation of DevOps; focusing specifically on building reliable systems, whereas DevOps covers a broader scope of operations.
[src:incident-management-deep/site-reliability-engineering] Despite having different focuses, some companies have rebranded their operations teams to SRE teams.
[src:incident-management-deep/site-reliability-engineering] SRE teams collaborate with other departments within organizations to guide the implementation of the mentioned principles.
[src:incident-management-deep/site-reliability-engineering] Kitchen Sink refers to the expansive and often unbounded scope of services and workflows that SRE teams oversee.
[src:incident-management-deep/site-reliability-engineering] Unlike traditional roles with clearly defined boundaries, SREs are tasked with various responsibilities, including system performance optimization, incident management, and automation.
[src:incident-management-deep/site-reliability-engineering] This approach allows SREs to address multiple challenges, ensuring that systems run efficiently and evolve in response to changing demands and complexities.
[src:incident-management-deep/site-reliability-engineering] Infrastructure SRE teams focus on maintaining and improving the reliability of systems that support other teams' workflows.
[src:incident-management-deep/site-reliability-engineering] While they sometimes collaborate with platform engineering teams, their primary responsibility is ensuring up-time, performance, and efficiency.
[src:incident-management-deep/site-reliability-engineering] Platform teams, on the other hand, primarily develop the software and systems used across the organization.
[src:incident-management-deep/site-reliability-engineering] While reliability is a goal for both, platform teams prioritize creating and maintaining the tools and services used by internal stakeholders, whereas Infrastructure SRE teams are tasked with ensuring those systems run smoothly and meet reliability standards.
[src:incident-management-deep/site-reliability-engineering] SRE teams utilize a variety of tools with the aim of measuring, maintaining, and enhancing system reliability.
[src:incident-management-deep/site-reliability-engineering] These tools play a role in monitoring performance, identifying issues, and facilitating proactive maintenance.
[src:incident-management-deep/site-reliability-engineering] For instance, Nagios Core is commonly employed for system monitoring and alerting, while Prometheus (software) is frequently used for collecting and querying metrics in cloud-native environments.
[src:incident-management-deep/site-reliability-engineering] SRE teams dedicated to specific products or applications are common in large organizations.
[src:incident-management-deep/site-reliability-engineering] These teams are responsible for ensuring the reliability, scalability, and performance of key services.
[src:incident-management-deep/site-reliability-engineering] In larger companies, it's typical to have multiple SRE teams, each focusing on different products or applications, ensuring that each area receives specialized attention to meet performance and availability targets.
[src:incident-management-deep/site-reliability-engineering] In an embedded model, individual SREs or small SRE pairs are integrated within software engineering teams.
[src:incident-management-deep/site-reliability-engineering] These SREs collaborate with developers, applying core SRE principles—such as automation, monitoring, and incident response—directly to the software development lifecycle.
[src:incident-management-deep/site-reliability-engineering] This approach aims to enhance reliability, performance, and collaboration between SREs and developers.
[src:incident-management-deep/site-reliability-engineering] Consulting SRE teams specialize in advising organizations on the implementation of SRE principles and practices.
[src:incident-management-deep/site-reliability-engineering] Typically composed of seasoned SREs with a history across various implementations, these teams provide insights and guidance for specific organizational needs.
[src:incident-management-deep/site-reliability-engineering] In large organizations that have adopted SRE, a hybrid model is common.
[src:incident-management-deep/site-reliability-engineering] This model includes various implementations, such as multiple Product/Application SRE teams dedicated to addressing the specific reliability needs of different products.
[src:incident-management-deep/site-reliability-engineering] An Infrastructure SRE team may collaborate with a Platform engineering group to achieve shared reliability goals for a unified platform that supports all products and applications.
[src:incident-management-deep/site-reliability-engineering] Since 2014, the USENIX organization has hosted the annual SREcon conference, bringing together site reliability engineers from various industries.
[src:incident-management-deep/site-reliability-engineering] This conference is a platform for professionals to share knowledge, explore effective practices, and discuss trends in site reliability engineering.
